{Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer; he expects you to bid 2\S. However, with such great \S support and an outside doubleton your hand now revalues to 18 points - more than an opening 1NT. You indicate this with a jump to 3\S. This is called a "Super-Accept".  Partner now bids 4NT. What do you answer? 

Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer; he expects you to bid 2\S. However, with such great \S support and an outside doubleton your hand now revalues to 18 points - more than an opening 1NT. You indicate this with a jump to 3\S. This is called a "Super-Accept".  Partner now bids 4NT. What do you answer?

Blackwood, and with one Ace you answer 5\D. Partner bids 6\S and everybody passes.

Obviously you aren't going to hold up on the \C lead. It won't matter where you take it, but assume you win in your hand.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = 0 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 2

Since the \D loser is a sure thing you will need to find somewhere to discard a \C. There are three possibilities:Finesse East for the \HQ. (50% chance)Try to drop the \HQ by ruffing the third round. (also about 50%)Establish a \D honor. (100% certain) 

First pull trumps, ending in dummy. It takes two rounds. Next play the \D5 toward your \DQ. East wins this and plays another \C. Win the \C, come to your hand with the \HK, then play your good \DQ, discarding dummy's losing \C.

You will need to ruff two \Hs in your hand, but the rest of the tricks are yours.

This was pretty easy because the trumps split 2-2.

If they had been 3-1 you would have had to leave the last trump undrawn until after you had ruffed two \Hs in your hand.}
[Play "W"]CT

