{In response to partner's Stayman bid you show your 4-card \S suit. Partner now bids 2NT.  

In response to partners Stayman bid you show your 4-card \S suit. Partner now bids 2NT. 

You may disagree with the Stayman bid on 3-4-3-3 distribution. In any case, 2NT is invitational, so with 17 points you say 3NT.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \HJ.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 3/4 : \D = 2 : \C = 2 :: Total = 7/8

East's \HJ lead probably means \Hs won't be 3-3, so you will need to get 2 \S tricks.

Suppose you win the first trick and plunk down the \SQ. If West wins with a doubleton \S honor you will only be able to win 1 \S since East will sit there with \S A 9 or \S K 9 behind your \S J 10. 

Instead, win the first trick in dummy and play a small \S toward the \S Q J 10. West will play low and East must take his \S honor. But you can win his return, enter dummy and play another \S toward your hand. If you are lucky, West will be forced to play an honor and you can toss your \S5.

to see if you were lucky. 

This plan, leading toward your \S holding twice, will succeed the majority of the time.

It only fails if East holds 4 or more \Ss headed by A K.}
[Play "W"]HJ

