{A square hand, no 4-card Major, and 9 points. This is the very hand that the book said to bid 2NT with. And when you do, partner says 3NT which you pass.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \C2. You must be living right, West gives you a trick with the opening lead.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 2 : \D = 1 : \C = 4 :: Total = 8

You got a good break on the opening lead, now you need only one more winner. There is <b>NO CHANCE</b> of creating another winner in \Ss, \Hs or \Cs, so your second good break is that you know it will have to be \Ds. 

You <b>COULD</b> lead toward dummy's \DQ, finessing West for the \DK. That would be a perfectly good 50% chance. But there is an even better play if you look carefully. 

Play a \D from your hand and if West plays low insert the \D9. Much of the time East will win with the \DJ or \D10. If so you are no worse off, you play West for the \DK. But if it happens that West was dealt both the \DJ and \D10 then East will have to win that trick with the \DK, or perhaps not even win it at all!

As you see, the Deep Finesse of the \D9 pays off here, where the straightforward finesse of the \DQ would lose the contract. Two chances are definitely better than one.

But what if West has played the \D10, splitting his honors?

You would put on dummy's \DQ and East would win the \DK. But you aren't down yet! Later you lead another \D toward dummy's \D A 9 and finesse West for the \DJ. }
[Play "W"]C2

