{Partner's 3\C bid is Stayman; with no 4-card Major you respond 3\D. Partner now bids 4\D.  

Partner's 3\C bid is Stayman; with no 4-card Major you respond 3\D. Partner now bids 4\D.  

Partner wouldn't bypass 3NT unless he was pretty distributional. His bid is invitational and you have excellent \D help so you try 5\D. 

North plays 5\D. East leads the \SQ.

You may be wishing partner had said 3NT. But at 3NT East might have led a \H, then you'd be wishing you were in 5\D.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 1 : \C = 0 :: Total = 2

This looks so easy let's check it by trying a winner count as well. Five \Ds (after \DA is gone), the \S A K, the \HA and the \C A K Q. Yes that adds up to 11 winners.

Is there ANY danger here at all? 

Whenever a hand looks easy you should ask yourself what could go wrong. And here the only thing that could go wrong is if one of your \S winners gets ruffed. So how can you prevent that possibility? 

If West has a singleton \S, and East has the \DA you might go down if you win the first trick in your hand. East will take his \DA and play the \SJ. If you go up with dummy's \SK West will ruff and you will still have a \S loser.

The simple solution is to win the first trick with dummy's \SK. Now when East wins the \DA and leads another \S it's a different situation. West may well ruff, but if he does you will just play a low card - West will have ruffed your \S <b>LOSER</b>.

You are a little unlucky that West has a singleton \S.

But you are very lucky that you took the time to read this hand so you know how to play safely!}
[Play "W"]SQ

