[Student "S"]
{You don't have enough points to be thinking about slam and you don't particularly want to play 5\D. So you bid 3NT and everybody passes.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \S6; East plays the \SJ.

Your immediate problem is whether or not to hold up. ? ? ?

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 3 : \D = 3 : \C = 1 :: Total = 8

There is some merit in a holdup. East is likely to have just 2 \Ss, so a holdup would exhaust his cards in the suit. If he later got the lead he would have no \Ss. On the other hand, East might well switch to \Cs, and that would certainly be unwelcome. Finally, if you do win the first \S you have another stopper if you can prevent East from getting the lead. So win the first trick with the \SK. Notice that by winning with the \SK you keep West in the dark as to whether you or East has the \SQ.

You need just one more trick, and either red suit might split 3-3. So is that your plan? Lead out red winners and hope? 

Truthfully, that wouldn't be a terrible plan. The chance of a 3-3 split in a suit is about 36%. But since you need either of two 36% chances that comes to almost 60% (if you aren't Math oriented don't worry about it, you can trust me).

There's a safer approach though; remember you only need 4 \D tricks, not 5. 

There is a wonderful "safety play" that will practically guarantee your contract. Enter dummy with a \H, then play a small \D toward your hand and finesse with your \D10! West may win with the \DJ, but even if he does he is the Safe Hand and cannot play a \S without giving you a trick. And whatever else he could play you would win and make 4 \D tricks. In the actual Deal the \D finesse actually works and you make all 5 tricks in the suit.

The only way this plan could go wrong is if West held the singleton \DJ. And if that were the case you wouldn't make the contract anyway (unless \Hs were 3-3).}
[Play "W"]S6

