{When you are 5-5 in the Majors you can transfer to either suit. Most will say transfer first to \Hs when you have invitational strength. So you bid 2\D.

Partner says 2\H;  

When you are 5-5 in the Majors you can transfer to either suit. Most will say transfer first to \Hs when you have invitational strength. So you bid 2\D.

Partner says 2\H; 

Now you show your other 5-card Major by bidding 2\S. This one hits the spot and partner raises to 4\S.

South plays 4\S. West leads the \H5. East takes the \HA and returns the \H6 which West ruffs. West then plays the \D2.

Loser List: \S = 0 : \H = 2 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 4

That's an odd way to show the second \H loser but you get the idea. You've lost 2 tricks already and it doesn't look like you can dodge the \CA. Soooooo, you cannot afford to lose a \D trick. 

Take dummy's \DA and then play \SA, \SK, relaxing a little when both defenders follow suit both times. 

Play your three high \Hs, discarding all three \Ds from dummy. Play your \C toward the \CK. West will no doubt grab his \CA but the rest will be yours, since you can ruff your \D loser in dummy. 

It was a little unlucky to suffer that early \H ruff.

But it was very very lucky that the ruffer happened to be the defender with three trumps!

That meant you could pull trumps with two pulls, leaving that one important one in dummy.}
[Play "W"]H5

