{Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer; you respond 2\S. Partner now bids 3\S.   

Partner's 2\H bid is a transfer; you respond 2\S. Partner now bids 3\S.   

You wouldn't have chosen \Ss for a trump suit.

But you aren't doing the choosing, partner is. He has set the trump suit as \Ss and asks that you bid game if you have a maximum 1NT opening. So you bid 4\S, as instructed.

North plays 4\S. East leads \HK, West plays \HJ. You have no reason to hold up so you win the \HA.

Loser List: \S = ? : \H = 2 : \D = 0 : \C = 0 :: Total = ?

Things look simple. You can afford one \S loser so as long as they split 3-2 you will succeed. So you play \SA, \SK; East follows to the first and discards a \D on the second. 

OK, West has two trump tricks, but don't give up. Maybe, just maybe, there is a way out. Check your winners:You have won 3 tricks - \HA and \S A K. You have 4 more top winners - \DA and \C A K Q. If you can somehow add 3 more small trumps that will be the 10 you need. 

Play dummy's \D7 to your \DA, then ruff a \D. Play a \C to your hand and ruff another \D. Play another \C to your hand and ruff your last \D. While you are ruffing these three \Ds West is helplessly following suit.

Now play to your good \C while West again has to follow suit.

You have taken the first 10 tricks. Poor West is going to end up ruffing his partner's \D winner with one of his master trumps.

Trumps don't always split as evenly as you would like them to.

When they split badly, sometimes you can recover by ruffing with small trumps while the trump-heavy defender has to follow suit.

This is called "trump elopement".}
[Play "W"]HK

