{Partner's 2NT bid invites you to bid game if you have a maximum hand. With 17 points you bid the game.

North plays 3NT. East leads the \C6. You play the \C4 from dummy, West plays the \CT and you take your \CQ.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 3 : \D = 1 : \C = 1 :: Total = 5

You are pretty sure East has the \CA so dummy's \CK can become a winner. If so, you only need 3 more winners.

All 3 can come from the \D suit if the finesse works, only 2 if it fails. Assume the worst, so that means you will also need a \S winner. 

When you give up the lead the opponents are going to continue \Cs if they can. If East has a 5-card \C suit you could lose 3 \Cs, the \SA and the \DK. Either defender might win the \SA, but only West can win with the \DK.  

Since East, the Danger hand, can only get in with the \SA you should establish a \S winner first, even though the \Ds are better. Whoever wins the \SA will probably knock out dummy's \CK. Hopefully this will not cause you a problem because when your finesse for the \DK loses to West he won't have another \C. At least that's the Plan!

If you finesse in \Ds first, West will return his last \C and the suit will get established while East still has an entry in the \SA.

Play \Ss first and even though East can win and establish \Cs West will not have a \C to return when he wins his \DK.

It goes without saying that if your \SK holds the trick you immediately switch to \Ds.}
[Play "W"]C6

