{With 12 points and no 4-card Major suit this one is easy. You bid 3NT of course.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \ST and East follows with the \S2.

Winner List: \S = 3 : \H = 2 : \D = 3 : \C = 0 :: Total = 8

There is just no way your ninth winner can come from \Ss, \Hs, or \Ds. So by process of elimination you have to get a \C trick.

Win the first trick, probably in your hand, and play a \C. 

A defender will definitely win this, and probably continue \Ss (but if they switch you would play the same way). You win the \S and play another \C. 

West wins and plays another \S; you win and play another \C. Deja vu. 

West wins again, cashed his established \S, and exits with a red card. You win and claim the rest of the tricks, including your now-established \C.

You were able to establish a \C because that suit split 3-2.

And you did it without going down because the \Ss split 4-3.

This may seem lucky to you, but don't knock it, it was your <b>ONLY</b> chance.}
[Play "W"]ST

