{Your partnership may play that a jump to 3\H shows a 6-card suit with slam interest, in other words, this very hand. If you do, then bid it. If you don't, use a transfer first. Let's say you bid 2\D. Partner jumps to 3\H. Now  

Your partnership may play that a jump to 3\H shows a 6-card suit with slam interest, in other words, this very hand. If you do, then bid it. If you don't, use a transfer first. Let's say you bid 2\D. Partner jumps to 3\H. Now 

You might just go ahead and bid 6\H. Partner probably has at least two Aces for his strong bidding. The other choice is a Blackwood 4NT, and this is certainly not the type of hand where asking for Aces is always helpful - what if partner shows two Aces, aren't you going to bid the slam anyway? The advantage to Blackwood here is that there is just a slim possibility that partner has only one Ace!

You bid 4NT and partner replies 5\S. Next? 

Your partnership may play that a jump to 3\H shows a 6-card suit with slam interest, in other words, this very hand. If you do, then bid it. If you don't, use a transfer first. Let's say you bid 2\D. Partner jumps to 3\H. Now  You might just go ahead and bid 6\H. Partner probably has at least two Aces for his strong bidding. The other choice is a Blackwood 4NT, and this is certainly not the type of hand where asking for Aces is always helpful - what if partner shows two Aces, aren't you going to bid the slam anyway? The advantage to Blackwood here is that there is just a slim possibility that partner has only one Ace! You bid 4NT and partner replies 5\S. Next? Three Aces. You still should stop at 6\H, based on points.

The contract would be 6\H played by South.

North plays 6\H. East leads the \CT. You play the \CJ, just in case East made a mistake, but West puts on the \CQ which you take with your \CA.

Loser List: \S = 1 : \H = 0 : \D = 0 : \C = 1 :: Total = 2

The \S loser is deceptive. You could discard a \S from dummy on your \DA, but would still have a \S loser if the finesse doesn't work. Still, this would be one possible plan. Can you improve on that? 

Maybe you can. Look harder at the \Ds. Win the \CA, then play to dummy's \DK. Pull trumps (2 rounds) ending in your hand. Play your \DA, but discard a \C from dummy, (the key play). Now play your \DJ, and if East plays low, discard dummy's other \C.

You have gotten rid of the \C losers, but if West can win the \DQ on this trick you will discard a \S on the \D10, but will still have to try the \S finesse.

But, if the \DJ holds then it won't matter if the \S finesse works or not, you will make the slam.

Suppose when you play your \DJ East puts on the \DQ.

No problem. You ruff in dummy, come back to your hand with a trump and <b>THEN</b> discard dummy's last \C on your \D10.

You can try the \S finesse then, but you will make the slam whether it works or not.}
[Play "W"]CT

