{With 12 points and a 5-card Major you transfer partner to that Major. You bid 2\H. Partner bids 2\S. Now what do say next? 

With 12 points and a 5-card Major you transfer partner to that Major. You bid 2\H. Partner bids 2\S. Now what do say next?

You must insist on game, but since partner could have a doubleton \S you do so by bidding 3NT to give him the choice.

He chooses 3NT by passing.

The contract would be 3NT played by North.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \DQ. Do you win the first trick or holdup?

Winner List: \S = 3 : \H = 0 : \D = 2 : \C = 3 :: Total = 8

A holdup wouldn't hurt you since West would retain the lead. But it probably wouldn't help you much either since you do have 2 stoppers in the suit. You obviously need to establish at least one more winner in \Ss so you won't have to depend on the \HA being with East. Need it be said that \Hs is the suit you are worried about and East is the Danger hand? Let's say you win the first trick with dummy's \DK. 

Suppose you play \SA, then \S K Q. If they split 3-3 you will be soooo happy because you will make at least 10 tricks. But if East shows out on the third \S you will be pretty happy because you can give up a \S to West and still make at least 9 tricks. But if West shows out on the third \S you could be in deep trouble. You would have to give East the lead to establish an extra \S winner, and he might very well lead through your \HK. 

There is a great safety play to protect against a 4-2 \S split. Play a low \S from dummy and finesse the \ST. West may win with a doubleton \SJ but you will still make the contract. 

With this layout the safety play finesse actually works and you make an overtrick.

But visualize the \SJ and \S7 transposed. If you don't make the safety play it is true that the \SJ will fall. BUT, East will still take the fourth \S and when he gets in he will return the \HQ.}
[Play "W"]DQ

