{Over an opponent's Weak 2-bid a 2NT overcall is used to show basically the same as a 1NT opening bid, but promising stopper(s) in their suit.

Partner bids 3NT.

South plays 3NT. West leads the \H10. As expected, West leads his partner's \H suit.

Winner List: \S = 1 : \H = 2 : \D = 2 : \C = 3 :: Total = 8

You need only one more winner; the best chance will be a 3-2 split in \Cs. But if that doesn't happen you might have to try the finesse in either \Ss or \Ds. The problem is that both finesses go into the East hand. Because of that fact there is no reason to hold up on the first trick so you win the \HA. Then you play the \CA . . . and East discards a \D! 

Don't be sad that the \Cs didn't split, your contract is now guaranteed! Well, guaranteed as long as East has only a 6-card \H suit.

Play your \HK, and when West follows suit play your \H7. East wins this trick and he can also win 3 more \H tricks. But when he runs out of \Hs he will be forced to play a \S or a \D because he doesn't have any \Cs. Either one will give you your ninth trick.

If the \Cs had split 4-1 you wouldn't know it until you played a second \C.

But it wouldn't matter, you would still play the same way. As long as you can strip East of any \Cs you can make the throw-in.}
[Play "W"]HT

