{It is tempting to just bid 3NT and hope the \Ds come in. But not when you have a 4-card Major suit. Instead you bid a Stayman 2\C. Partner says 2\S;  

It is tempting to just bid 3NT and hope the \Ds come in. But not when you have a 4-card Major suit. Instead you bid a Stayman 2\C. Partner says 2\S; 

Well, he has 4 \Ss. That's why you used Stayman so you bid 4\S.

The contract would be 4\S played by South.

North plays 4\S. East leads the \CK. Seeing 10 top tricks sort of makes you wish you had just bid 3NT.

Loser List: \S = 2/3/4 : \H = 0 : \D = 0 : \C = 0 :: Total = 2/3/4

Missing 5 \Ss, the most likely split is 3-2, (68% of the time). You win the \CA and play a small \S toward dummy. East puts on the \SQ which you take with dummy's \SA, West following with the \S6.

Do you play \Ss again? or not? 

Not. With both defenders following suit, the possibility of 4 \S losers is gone so you can lose at most 3. But that \SQ from East is ominous. If you play another \S and they do split 3-2 you will make 11 tricks, losing only 2 trumps. But if West has 3 \Ss left he will win the trick, pull all the rest of the trumps, and lead a \C to East.

The guaranteed way to make the contract is to play no more \Ss, but to start playing \D winners. The defenders can make their 3 trump tricks but you maintain control of the hand.

As you see, playing a second trump would have been disastrous.

But with a different distribution, (3-2), playing the second trump would have been great. 

Considering probabilities it looks like this. If you play the second trump you will make 2 overtricks about 70% of the time, but you will go down 4 about 30% of the time.

If you stop with the \Ss and start running \Ds you will make your contract 100% of the time but will never make an overtrick. }
[Play "W"]CK

